description.narrative: In Ghana, the programme will target 4.000 female miners, 90.000 people (men and women) in the mining communities and 300 female entrepreneurs. In Tanzania, GfG will target 2.400 female miners, 105.000 men and women in the mining communities and 250 female entrepreneurs.

Long term objective: Women in and around artisanal and small-scale gold mining communities in Ghana and Tanzania are more economically empowered. 1) Women have improved working conditions within gold mines A - Gold mines operate according to fair mine practices in support of women’s rights and needs 2) Women in mining communities have increased abilities to engage in economic activities A – Women in mining communities have improved SRHR B – Women have more time available to spend on economic activities. HE Foundation will primarily be focussed on the ability of women to be engaged in economic activities.

The Going for Gold programme is a collaboration between Simavi, Solidaridad and Healthy Entrepreneurs to improve the position of women working in gold mines in the area of health, safety and their economic position. Currently, the working conditions of women working in mines is hazardous and women are not empowered enough to claim their rights to equal wages, a safe working environment, and access to health facilities. Women regularly face Sexual and Gender Based Violence, which not only exposes them to unsolicited sex, unwanted pregnancies and the risk of contracting HIV/AIDS and sexually transmitted infections (STIs), but also significantly impacts women’s health and wellbeing. The programme will address these issues from a multi disciplinary approach; improving the working conditions of women in the mining industry, training women as health entrepreneurs to run viable businesses, and improving the Sexual and Reproductive Health of women in the mining communities.
